el-pose-with-her-kids.jpg","width":800,"height":450},{"@type":"BreadcrumbList","@id":"https://www.yogajournal.com/poses/two-fit-moms-6-tips-for-doing-yoga-with-your-kids/#breadcrumb","itemListElement":[{"@type":"ListItem","position":1,"name":"Yoga Poses","item":"https://www.yogajournal.com/poses/"},{"@type":"ListItem","position":2,"name":"6 Tips for Doing Yoga With Your Kids","item":"https://www.yogajournal.com/poses/two-fit-moms-6-tips-for-doing-yoga-with-your-kids/"}]},{"@type":"WebSite","@id":"https://www.yogajournal.com/#website","url":"https://www.yogajournal.com/","name":"Yoga Journal","description":"Yoga Journal | Yoga Poses - Sequences - Philosophy - Events","publisher":{"@id":"https://www.yogajournal.com/#organization"},"potentialAction":[{"@type":"SearchAction","target":{"@type":"EntryPoint","urlTemplate":"https://www.yogajournal.com/?s={search_term_string}"},"query-input":"required name=search_term_string"}],"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"Organization","@id":"https://www.yogajournal.com/#organization","name":"Yoga Journal","url":"https://www.yogajournal.com/","logo":{"@type":"ImageObject","inLanguage":"en-US","@id":"https://www.yogajournal.com/#/schema/logo/image/","url":"https://cdn.outsideonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/AF-YOGA_JOURNAL.png","contentUrl":"https://cdn.outsideonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/AF-YOGA_JOURNAL.png","width":250,"height":250,"caption":"Yoga Journal"},"image":{"@id":"https://www.yogajournal.com/#/schema/logo/image/"}},{"@type":"Person","@id":"https://www.yogajournal.com/#/schema/person/4645","name":"Masumi Goldman","url":"https://www.yogajournal.com/byline/masumi-goldman"}]}</script><div class="mt-[116px]"><div aria-label="Advertisement" class="prestitial-ad mx-auto my-tight min-h-[274px] w-full bg-bg-very-light py-base-tight sm:px-base-tight"><div id="prestitial-0" class="prestitial-content"></div></div></div><div class="mx-auto flex max-w-[1440px] px-base sm:px-loose md:space-x-base-loose md:p-base-loose lg:p-base" data-testid="grid"><div class="grid w-full grid-cols-4 gap-base-loose sm:grid-cols-8 md:grid-cols-12 body-content js-body-content overflow-x-hidden body-content-dense"><div class="col-span-full"></div><div class="article-header !col-span-full flex flex-col text-left"><div class="justify-start"><nav class="align-left col-span-full mb-base" data-pom-e2e-test-id="breadcrumbs"><ul class="flex flex-wrap gap-super-tight font-semibold"><li class="!-ml-0.5 flex gap-super-tight whitespace-nowrap"><a class="rounded-small px-extra-tight font-utility-2 text-brand-primary transition-colors duration-400 hover:bg-bg-light active:bg-bg-medium" href="/poses"><span>Yoga Poses</span></a></li></ul></nav><h1 class="mb-base-loose text-text-headline">6 Tips for Doing Yoga With Your Kids</h1><div class="fp-intro mb-loose font-secondary text-description-size leading-description-line-height font-normal text-secondary">If our kids are any indication, we at Two Fit Moms think it’s likely that your kids want to practice yoga with you. So this week, in honor of Mother&#x27;s Day, we are offering our best tips for making it work.</div></div><div class="border-border-light border-t py-base-tight"><div class="flex h-4 justify-between"><div class="flex gap-x-base-tight"></div><div class="flex gap-x-base-tight"><div class="relative"><button class="inline-flex shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full hover:cursor-pointer bg-bg-surface hover:bg-bg-light focus:bg-bg-dark text-primary border border-solid border-border-light aria-pressed:bg-brand-primary aria-pressed:text-text-surface py-very-tight px-base-tight gap-tight font-semibold font-utility-2" aria-label="Share article" aria-pressed="false" id="" aria-haspopup="true"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" class=""><title>Share Icon</title><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M9.52671 2.21112C9.31975 2.29685 9.18481 2.4988 9.18481 2.72281V5.69328C4.9997 6.2414 1.80019 10.0091 1.80019 14.533V15.2767C1.80019 15.5374 1.9821 15.7629 2.23697 15.818C2.49185 15.8731 2.75065 15.743 2.8584 15.5055C3.80204 13.4258 6.21665 11.8364 9.18481 11.6591V14.5382C9.18481 14.7622 9.31975 14.9642 9.52671 15.0499C9.73367 15.1356 9.97189 15.0882 10.1303 14.9298L16.038 9.02213C16.2543 8.80584 16.2543 8.45516 16.038 8.23887L10.1303 2.33118C9.97189 2.17278 9.73367 2.1254 9.52671 2.21112ZM10.2925 11.0903C10.2925 11.0898 10.2925 11.0893 10.2925 11.0888C10.2925 10.783 10.0445 10.535 9.73866 10.535C7.00766 10.535 4.54501 11.6113 2.99576 13.3185C3.52188 9.72192 6.34795 6.97376 9.77511 6.7477C10.0662 6.7285 10.2925 6.48678 10.2925 6.19505V4.05991L14.8631 8.6305L10.2925 13.2011V11.0918C10.2925 11.0913 10.2925 11.0908 10.2925 11.0903Z" class="fill-inverse"></path></svg><span class="hidden sm:inline">Share</span></button></div><button class="inline-flex shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full hover:cursor-pointer bg-bg-surface hover:bg-bg-light focus:bg-bg-dark text-primary border border-solid border-border-light aria-pressed:bg-brand-primary aria-pressed:text-text-surface py-very-tight px-base-tight gap-tight font-semibold font-utility-2 sm:w-10.75" aria-label="Save this article" aria-pressed="false" id="article-bookmark-button"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="current-color" class=""><title>Bookmark Icon</title><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M5.89753 3.23089C5.40785 3.23089 4.93823 3.42541 4.59198 3.77166C4.24572 4.11792 4.0512 4.58754 4.0512 5.07722V16.564C4.0512 16.6021 4.06181 16.6394 4.08183 16.6718C4.10186 16.7042 4.13051 16.7304 4.16459 16.7474C4.19866 16.7645 4.2368 16.7717 4.27474 16.7683C4.31268 16.7649 4.34892 16.751 4.3794 16.7281L9.63131 12.7907C9.8501 12.6267 10.1509 12.6267 10.3697 12.7907L15.6216 16.7281C15.652 16.751 15.6883 16.7649 15.7262 16.7683C15.7642 16.7717 15.8023 16.7645 15.8364 16.7474C15.8705 16.7304 15.8991 16.7042 15.9191 16.6718C15.9392 16.6394 15.9498 16.6021 15.9498 16.564V5.07722C15.9498 4.58754 15.7552 4.11792 15.409 3.77166C15.0627 3.42541 14.5931 3.23089 14.1034 3.23089H5.89753ZM3.72161 2.9013C4.2987 2.32421 5.0814 2 5.89753 2H14.1034C14.9196 2 15.7023 2.32421 16.2794 2.9013C16.8565 3.47839 17.1807 4.26109 17.1807 5.07722V16.564C17.1807 16.8306 17.1064 17.092 16.9662 17.3189C16.826 17.5457 16.6255 17.7291 16.387 17.8483C16.1485 17.9676 15.8815 18.0181 15.6159 17.9942C15.3503 17.9703 15.0966 17.8729 14.8832 17.713L10.0005 14.0523L5.11775 17.713C4.90439 17.8729 4.6507 17.9703 4.38511 17.9942C4.11952 18.0181 3.85251 17.9676 3.61401 17.8483C3.37551 17.7291 3.17493 17.5457 3.03475 17.3189C2.89456 17.092 2.82031 16.8306 2.82031 16.564V5.07722C2.82031 4.26109 3.14452 3.47839 3.72161 2.9013Z" class="fill-inverse"></path></svg><span class="hidden sm:inline">Save</span></button></div></div></div><div><img alt="Masumi Goldman doing Camel Pose with her kids." data-src="https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/masumi-goldman-doing-camel-pose-with-her-kids.jpg" data-loaded="true" fetchPriority="high" loading="eager" width="1440" height="450" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color:transparent" srcSet="https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/masumi-goldman-doing-camel-pose-with-her-kids.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=1920&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover 1x, https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/masumi-goldman-doing-camel-pose-with-her-kids.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=3840&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover 2x" src="https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/masumi-goldman-doing-camel-pose-with-her-kids.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=3840&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover"/></div></div><div class="content-wrap fp-contentTarget"><div class="article-body"><div class="mb-base-loose flex flex-wrap gap-(--spacing-base)"><!--$--><div class="fp-remove flex items-center justify-start gap-(--spacing-base-tight)"><a href="/byline/masumi-goldman" data-outbound-instanced="true" class="flex items-center justify-start gap-(--spacing-base-tight)" aria-label="View Masumi Goldman&#x27;s bio"><span class="font-utility-2 font-bold text-primary">Masumi Goldman</span></a></div><!--/$--><!--$--><div class="fp-remove flex items-center justify-start gap-(--spacing-base-tight)"><a href="/byline/laura-kasperzak" data-outbound-instanced="true" class="flex items-center justify-start gap-(--spacing-base-tight)" aria-label="View Laura Kasperzak&#x27;s bio"><span class="font-utility-2 font-bold text-primary">Laura Kasperzak</span></a></div><!--/$--></div><div class="pub-date font-utility-2 text-secondary">Published May 5, 2016 07:53PM</div><div class="mt-base-loose"></div></div><p>Kids, almost inevitably, can get in the way of a parent’s yoga practice—in our case, quite literally. Since yoga is such a significant part of our lives, and we both generally practice at home, it was only natural for us to invite our children on the mat. It wasn’t a hard sell—our kids wanted to be a part of our yoga, which was great and very welcome.</p><p class="aspect-video"></p><p>If our kids are any indication, we at <a target="_blank" class="article-content-link text-brand-primary underline hover:text-brand-primary/85 break-words overflow-wrap-anywhere underline-offset-[3px]" data-afl-p="0" href="http://www.twofitmoms.com">Two Fit Moms</a> think it’s likely that your kids would love to practice yoga with you. So this week, in honor of Mother’s Day, we are offering 6 tips for doing yoga with your kids.</p>
<h3>1. Focus on the basics.</h3>
<figure class="pom-image-wrap alignnone"><img title="Masumi doing Tree Pose with her kids." alt="Masumi doing Tree Pose with her kids." loading="lazy" width="1100" height="400" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color:transparent" srcSet="https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/masumi-doing-tree-pose-with-her-kids.jpg?width=1200&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover 1x, https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/masumi-doing-tree-pose-with-her-kids.jpg?width=3840&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover 2x" src="https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/masumi-doing-tree-pose-with-her-kids.jpg?width=3840&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover"/></figure>
<p>Kids love <a target="_self" class="article-content-link text-brand-primary underline hover:text-brand-primary/85 break-words overflow-wrap-anywhere underline-offset-[3px]" data-afl-p="0" href="https://www.yogajournal.com/pose/downward-facing-dog/">Downward-Facing Dog</a>, <a target="_self" class="article-content-link text-brand-primary underline hover:text-brand-primary/85 break-words overflow-wrap-anywhere underline-offset-[3px]" data-afl-p="0" href="https://www.yogajournal.com/pose/tree-pose/">Tree Pose</a>, <a target="_self" class="article-content-link text-brand-primary underline hover:text-brand-primary/85 break-words overflow-wrap-anywhere underline-offset-[3px]" data-afl-p="0" href="https://www.yogajournal.com/pose/warrior-ii-pose/">Warrior II</a>, and <a target="_self" class="article-content-link text-brand-primary underline hover:text-brand-primary/85 break-words overflow-wrap-anywhere underline-offset-[3px]" data-afl-p="0" href="https://www.yogajournal.com/pose/easy-pose/">Easy Pose</a>. These are great beginner poses, in general.</p>
<p>Tree Pose is a great single-leg balance to practice with your children. Hold hands to link your trees together and create a forest. This is a fun way to help your kids balance while building their confidence in their abilities.</p>
<div class="ad-placeholder-wrapper relative w-full border-t border-b border-border-light col-span-full my-3 md:col-span-10 md:col-start-2"><div class="mb-[30px] min-h-[30px] text-center"><span class="font-utility-4 font-medium tracking-[1px] text-neutral-500 uppercase">ADVERTISEMENT</span></div><div class="ad-placeholder -mt-[30px] mb-[30px] flex min-h-[250px] w-full items-center justify-center"><div class="w-full "><div id="in-content-leaderboard-in-content-leaderboard-I0-P0-CMI0" class="flex justify-center text-left"></div></div></div></div><h3>2. Let them surprise you.</h3>
<figure class="pom-image-wrap alignnone"><img title="Laura doing yoga with her daughter." alt="Laura doing yoga with her daughter." loading="lazy" width="1100" height="400" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color:transparent" srcSet="https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/laura-doing-yoga-with-her-daughter.jpg?width=1200&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover 1x, https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/laura-doing-yoga-with-her-daughter.jpg?width=3840&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover 2x" src="https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/laura-doing-yoga-with-her-daughter.jpg?width=3840&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover"/></figure>
<p>Teach them what they should be doing, and don’t fret if their poses aren’t perfect. Your kids may surprise you. This AcroYoga pose with my daughter did exactly that—I never expected her to get into this posture, and I don’t think she expected to either!</p>
<p>Yoga with my daughter is all about having fun. But in between the giggles, I see glimmers of her own practice taking shape, which is very exciting for me to watch.</p>
<p><em>See also</em><a target="_self" class="article-content-link text-brand-primary underline hover:text-brand-primary/85 break-words overflow-wrap-anywhere underline-offset-[3px]" data-afl-p="0" href="https://www.yogajournal.com/slideshow/two-fit-moms-grounding-gravity-defying-earth-day-yoga-poses/">Two Fit Moms’ Gravity-Defying Earth Day Flow</a></p>
<h3>3. Play with animal poses.</h3>
<figure class="pom-image-wrap alignnone"><img title="Masumi Goldman doing Camel Pose with her kids." alt="Masumi Goldman doing Camel Pose with her kids." loading="lazy" width="1100" height="400" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color:transparent" srcSet="https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/masumi-goldman-doing-camel-pose-with-her-kids.jpg?width=1200&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover 1x, https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/masumi-goldman-doing-camel-pose-with-her-kids.jpg?width=3840&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover 2x" src="https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/masumi-goldman-doing-camel-pose-with-her-kids.jpg?width=3840&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover"/></figure>
<p>Consider focusing on the animal-named poses like <a target="_self" class="article-content-link text-brand-primary underline hover:text-brand-primary/85 break-words overflow-wrap-anywhere underline-offset-[3px]" data-afl-p="0" href="https://www.yogajournal.com/pose/camel-pose/">Camel</a>, Butterfly (<a target="_self" class="article-content-link text-brand-primary underline hover:text-brand-primary/85 break-words overflow-wrap-anywhere underline-offset-[3px]" data-afl-p="0" href="https://www.yogajournal.com/poses/bound-angle-pose-2/ ">Bound Angle Pose</a>), <a target="_self" class="article-content-link text-brand-primary underline hover:text-brand-primary/85 break-words overflow-wrap-anywhere underline-offset-[3px]" data-afl-p="0" href="https://www.yogajournal.com/poses/cobra-pose-2/ ">Cobra</a>, <a target="_self" class="article-content-link text-brand-primary underline hover:text-brand-primary/85 break-words overflow-wrap-anywhere underline-offset-[3px]" data-afl-p="0" href="https://www.yogajournal.com/pose/cat-pose/">Cat</a>/<a target="_self" class="article-content-link text-brand-primary underline hover:text-brand-primary/85 break-words overflow-wrap-anywhere underline-offset-[3px]" data-afl-p="0" href="https://www.yogajournal.com/pose/cow-pose/">Cow</a>, etc. These postures will resonate with them and are ones that will allow them to be more playful and silly.</p>
<p>Camel Pose is a challenging backbend, but the good news is that it can be modified for kids in the same way that it can be modified for adults. Begin in a kneeling position with the thighs perpendicular to the floor, place your hands onto your lower back, fingers pointed down. Lift your chest and create an even backbend, avoiding collapsing into the lower back. If your children would like to attempt the full expression of the pose, encourage them to first try the pose with their toes tucked and heels lifted. Slowly reach one hand back at a time to hold each heel. If that goes well, they can try the version with toes untucked. Whichever version they attempt, just make sure that they are safe and having a good time.</p>
<div class="ad-placeholder-wrapper relative w-full border-t border-b border-border-light col-span-full my-3 md:col-span-10 md:col-start-2"><div class="mb-[30px] min-h-[30px] text-center"><span class="font-utility-4 font-medium tracking-[1px] text-neutral-500 uppercase">ADVERTISEMENT</span></div><div class="ad-placeholder -mt-[30px] mb-[30px] flex min-h-[250px] w-full items-center justify-center"><div class="w-full "><div id="in-content-leaderboard-in-content-leaderboard-I1-P0-CMI0" class="flex justify-center text-left"></div></div></div></div><p><em>See also</em><a target="_self" class="article-content-link text-brand-primary underline hover:text-brand-primary/85 break-words overflow-wrap-anywhere underline-offset-[3px]" data-afl-p="0" href="https://www.yogajournal.com/slideshow/two-fit-moms-backbending-practice/">Two Fit Moms’ Backbending Practice</a></p>
<h3>4. Add modifications to make it extra fun.</h3>
<figure class="pom-image-wrap alignnone"><img title="Laura Kasperzak of Two Fit Moms doing yoga with her daughter." alt="Laura Kasperzak of Two Fit Moms doing yoga with her daughter." loading="lazy" width="1100" height="400" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color:transparent" srcSet="https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/laura-kasperzak-of-two-fit-moms-doing-yoga-with-her-daughter.jpg?width=1200&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover 1x, https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/laura-kasperzak-of-two-fit-moms-doing-yoga-with-her-daughter.jpg?width=3840&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover 2x" src="https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/laura-kasperzak-of-two-fit-moms-doing-yoga-with-her-daughter.jpg?width=3840&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover"/></figure>
<p>Kids are naturally flexible so they love <a target="_self" class="article-content-link text-brand-primary underline hover:text-brand-primary/85 break-words overflow-wrap-anywhere underline-offset-[3px]" data-afl-p="0" href="https://www.yogajournal.com/poses/cobra-pose-2/ ">Cobra Pose</a>—especially if you ask them to try to touch their toes to their head! Partnering with mom makes it extra fun.</p>
<p><em>See also</em><a target="_self" class="article-content-link text-brand-primary underline hover:text-brand-primary/85 break-words overflow-wrap-anywhere underline-offset-[3px]" data-afl-p="0" href="https://www.yogajournal.com/slideshow/two-fit-moms-heart-opening-partner-yoga/">Two Fit Moms’ Heart-Opening Partner Yoga Sequence</a></p>
<h3>5. Don’t expect them to do a full practice.</h3>
<figure class="pom-image-wrap alignnone"><img title="Masumi Goldman&#x27;s kids doing Tree Pose." alt="Masumi Goldman&#x27;s kids doing Tree Pose." loading="lazy" width="1100" height="400" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color:transparent" srcSet="https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/masumi-goldmans-kids-doing-tree-pose.jpg?width=1200&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover 1x, https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/masumi-goldmans-kids-doing-tree-pose.jpg?width=3840&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover 2x" src="https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/masumi-goldmans-kids-doing-tree-pose.jpg?width=3840&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover"/></figure>
<p>We know this sounds obvious, but when our kids started to join us, we thought they would just fall in love with yoga and practice for a full 30–45 minutes. WRONG. Children under the age of 10 do not typically have the attention span, but they can manage 5–10 minutes on the mat. So, start with small intervals of time.</p>
<p><em>See also</em><a target="_self" class="article-content-link text-brand-primary underline hover:text-brand-primary/85 break-words overflow-wrap-anywhere underline-offset-[3px]" data-afl-p="0" href="https://www.yogajournal.com/slideshow/good-morning-yoga-poses-jumpstart-kids-day/">Good Morning Yoga: A 3-Minute Flow to Jumpstart Your Kids’ Day</a></p>
<h3>6. Get them their own yoga gear.</h3>
<figure class="pom-image-wrap alignnone"><img title="Laura Kasperzak&#x27;s kids practice yoga on Gaiam yoga mats for kids." alt="Laura Kasperzak&#x27;s kids practice yoga on Gaiam yoga mats for kids." loading="lazy" width="1100" height="400" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color:transparent" srcSet="https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/laura-kasperzaks-kids-practice-yoga-on-gaiam-yoga-mats-for-kids.jpg?width=1200&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover 1x, https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/laura-kasperzaks-kids-practice-yoga-on-gaiam-yoga-mats-for-kids.jpg?width=3840&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover 2x" src="https://cdn.yogajournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/laura-kasperzaks-kids-practice-yoga-on-gaiam-yoga-mats-for-kids.jpg?width=3840&amp;auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;fit=cover"/></figure>
<p>We don’t know about your kids, but ours love to have their own space and their own stuff. Fun <a target="_self" class="article-content-link text-brand-primary underline hover:text-brand-primary/85 break-words overflow-wrap-anywhere underline-offset-[3px]" data-afl-p="0" href="https://www.yogajournal.com/lifestyle/kids-yoga-mats/">yoga mats for kids</a> will make your little ones feel grown up—and you won’t have to share your mat!</p>
